The effect of love is variously described, as well as accounted for, by the poets. Generally, however, the instrument supposed to be employed, is either a dart from the eye, producing a wound, as in v, 36, of the present book ; or else a species of subtle and irresistible flame, eroding and consuming the bosom, as in the present passage. In the opening of book iv, of the AEneid,Virgil introduces both these metaphors,

Vulnus alit venis, et caeco carpitur igni. She feeds her wound‚ and pines with secret fire.
